  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">FAQs</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p>Common questions about rewards credit cards and earning points</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">How are reward points calculated on credit card spends?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Reward points are calculated based on a per-rupee or per-transaction formula set by the card issuer. For example, HDFC Regalia earns 4 reward points per ₹150 spent, meaning a ₹15,000 purchase earns 400 points. Some cards offer accelerated earning on specific categories — like 10X on partner brands or 5X on online shopping — where the multiplier applies on top of the base rate. Utility payments, fuel transactions, and EMI conversions are typically excluded from earning reward points.</div></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">What can I redeem my reward points for?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Reward points can be redeemed through your card issuer's rewards catalogue for a variety of options: (1) Air miles and flight bookings via partner airlines, (2) Hotel stays through partner programs, (3) Amazon, Flipkart, and brand-specific gift vouchers, (4) Physical merchandise and electronics, (5) Statement credits that reduce your bill, (6) Charity donations. Premium cards like HDFC Infinia allow 1:1 transfers to airline loyalty programs like Singapore Airlines KrisFlyer, Marriott Bonvoy, and InterMiles — offering the highest redemption value per point.</div></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">Do reward points expire?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">It depends on the card issuer. HDFC Bank reward points typically expire after 2-3 years from the date of earning. SBI Card reward points are valid for 2 years. Axis Bank EDGE Reward points expire after 3 years of inactivity. ICICI Bank rewards usually have no expiry as long as the card account is active. Always check your card's terms and conditions for the specific expiry policy. We recommend redeeming points periodically rather than accumulating them for too long to avoid expiry losses.</div></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">Which rewards card is best for online shopping?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">For online shopping, the best rewards cards are: (1) SBI SimplyCLICK — 10X rewards on partner sites like Amazon, Cleartrip, and Lenskart, (2) HDFC Millennia — 5% cashback on Amazon, Flipkart, and online spends, (3) ICICI Amazon Pay — 5% back on Amazon for Prime members, 2% on other online, (4) Axis Flipkart — 5% on Flipkart and Myntra. If you shop primarily on Amazon, the ICICI Amazon Pay card offers the best value as it's lifetime free with unlimited 5% back for Prime subscribers.</div></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">Is a rewards card better than a cashback card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">It depends on your preference. Cashback cards give you direct monetary credit on your statement — simple and straightforward with a clear return rate (typically 1-5%). Rewards cards, on the other hand, offer points that can deliver higher value when redeemed optimally (e.g., transferring to airline miles for premium flight redemptions). If you prefer simplicity and guaranteed returns, choose cashback. If you're willing to strategise your redemptions and want the potential for higher value (especially for travel), rewards cards are better. High spenders generally benefit more from rewards cards.</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Page CTA -->
  <section class="page-content" style="padding-top: 0;">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="page-cta">
        <div>
          <h3>Start Earning Rewards on Every Spend</h3>
          <p>Choose from India's top rewards credit cards, earn points on every transaction, and redeem for flights, vouchers, and more. Apply online in minutes.</p>
        </div>
        <a href="#" class="btn btn-outline">Apply Now <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Footer -->

